{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 4}
When [C]the train pulled out [F]poor Mother [C]stood weepin’
And sister she sat all alone with a [G]sigh
And the [C]last words I heard was [F]“Willy God [C]bless you”
Was [C]“Willy God bless you God bless you goodbye”
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 5}
In [C]the scorching hot sand of [F]the foundry [C]I’m workin’
Toiling and working my poor life [G]away
They’ll [C]measure my grave on [F]the banks of [C]old Cumberland
Just as soon as I finish the [G]rest of [C]my days
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 6}
Poort Martha was grave, but Corey was better
There’s better and worse, although you may see
Boys [C]when you write home from [F]this prison [C]in Nashville
